1. INTRODUCTION & BACKGROUND

1.1 The Limitations of Current Computing Paradigms

Modern computing faces fundamental limitations across three dimensions:

Quantum Computing Challenges:

· Extreme environmental requirements (10 mK temperatures)
· High error rates requiring extensive error correction
· Limited qubit coherence times
· Massive classical control overhead
· Energy-intensive cryogenic systems

Neuromorphic Computing Limitations:

· Restricted to classical information processing
· Limited scalability in weight storage
· Training convergence challenges
· Limited expressivity compared to quantum systems

Edge Computing Constraints:

· Severe power budgets (milliwatt to watt scale)
· Limited computational resources
· Real-time latency requirements
· Privacy and security concerns with cloud offloading

1.2 The Convergence Thesis

QENE proposes that the limitations of each paradigm can be addressed through their synergistic integration:

1. Quantum systems provide exponential parallelism and fundamentally new computational capabilities
2. Neuromorphic systems offer ultra-efficient, event-driven computation inspired by biological brains
3. Edge deployment ensures real-time processing, privacy preservation, and energy efficiency

The core insight: Quantum effects can enhance neural computation, while neural architectures can mitigate quantum decoherence, and both can be optimized for edge deployment.

1.3 Historical Context and Related Work

QENE builds upon decades of research across multiple fields:

· Quantum Machine Learning: Quantum algorithms for classical ML tasks (2008-present)
· Neuromorphic Computing: IBM TrueNorth (2014), Intel Loihi (2017), BrainChip Akida (2020)
· Edge AI: TensorFlow Lite (2017), NVIDIA Jetson series (2014-present)
· Quantum-Neural Interfaces: Preliminary theoretical work (2018-2023)

QENE represents the first comprehensive framework for co-design across all three domains, with complete hardware-software stack implementation.

